[normal]The LGO’s manipulative behaviour with regard to previous Ipsos-MORI Customer Satisfaction Surveys, detailed in my previous submissions, come
[normal]s immediately to mind here.
[normal]With regard to
[normal] the composition of the investigating Team, we are told:
[normal]"The Team was Chaired by Richard Thomas CBE, Chairman of the Administrative Justice and Tribunals Council and former Information Commissioner.1 The other mem
[normal]bers of the Team were Jim Martin, the current Scottish Public Services Ombudsman and former Police Complaints Commissioner for Scotland;2 and Dr Richard Kirkham,3 an academic from the University of Sheffield with previous research experience of ombudsman s
[normal]chemes." (P4)
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]So one member was a former Information Commissioner. Another was the current Scottish Public Service Ombudsman. And the third, Dr Richard Kirkham, was someone 
[normal]already very 
[normal]well-known to us at LGO Watch as one of the Local Government Ombudsma
[normal]n’s strongest sympathisers
[normal] and allies
[normal]. The following was published on the Ombudsmanwatchers’ website in 2009
[normal]. (The reference in it is to the 2005 select committee evidence session.)
[normal]“Following the damning evidence submitted to the select committee by a num
[normal]ber of complainants an article was written by Dr Richard Kirkham purporting to be a complainant's view of the Local Government Ombudsman (LGO). However, nothing could be further from the truth. We doubt Dr. Kirkham even bothered to speak to a complainant b
[normal]efore writing his article. His article is so pro LGO one could be excused for thinking it was written by a friend of the LGO. After reading his article we decided to find out just who 
[normal]Dr. 
[normal]Kirkham
[normal] was and soon discovered that far from being independent he, like the LGO, is also member of the BIOA. Things must be bad if the LGO have to get their friends and colleagues to write positive articles about them in order to shore up their 
[normal]evangelical agenda.
[normal]Dr. Kirkham states in his article 
[normal]'In a recent Parliamentary review of the work of the Local Government Ombudsman (LGO), the Select Committee on the Office of th
[normal]e Deputy Prime Minister received a number of submissions from dissatisfied users of the service provided by the LGO (Select Committee on the ODPM, 2004-2005, Ev 
[normal]16-28). In amongst these submissions, there were even proposals for the abolition of the LGO (i
[normal]bid., Ev 26). To a certain extent, such criticisms misunderstand the purpose of public sector redress mechanisms and the remit of the Ombudsmen.' 
[normal]Obviously he forgot about Sir Geoffrey Chipperfield effectively suggesting that during his 1995 review of the [bold]LGO.”[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Although Dr Kirkham made the claim for his article that it was a “Complainant’s view of the Local Government Ombudsman,” it was 
[normal]in fact 
[normal]nothing 
[normal]other
[normal] than a paean to the LGO at a time when the objectivity of the institution had been called into question by real complainants
[normal], such as myself
[normal]. 
[normal](It should also be noted that, despite the LGO’s attempts to dismiss dissatisfied complainants who were campaigni
[normal]ng to expose the bias of the LGO, in the case I brought to their attention, the LGO found administrative fault and suggested pecuniary compensation for the complainant I was representing. It was the appalling maladministration, dishonesty and subterfuge th
[normal]at I discovered in the course of this successful outcome being realised that caused me to set up LGO Watch. The campaign to abolish or reform the LGO was therefore started by the representative of a complainant who had achieved a successful outcome, albeit
[normal] that this outcome came about only because of a persistence and determination 
[normal]fuelled by my outrage at institutional injustice committed with impunity against so many people, some of whom were very vulnerable indeed
[normal].) 
[normal] 
[normal]Dr Kirkham’s article did not even indicate that he had ever submitted a complaint to the LGO, and so the claim to represent the perspective of a complainant when writing such a 
[normal]complimentary piece about the LGO
[normal] was highly questionable. 
[normal]It should also be n
[normal]oted 
[normal]that Dr Kirkham did not play a
[normal] minor role in the drafting of the “independent” External Evaluation. In the Preface, we are told: 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]"Richard Kirkham undertook the bulk of the research and drafting of this Report for which his colleagues are most gratef
[normal]ul." (p4)
[normal]&#xa0;
